[1
Date: Fri, 8 May 1998 10:57:41 -500
From: Dr. Juan Moreira <apostol1@ECUA.NET.ec>

Domesticated guinea pigs, locally named as "cuyes", not only are part of
the diet during the funeral activities, but families in Andean communities
breed a lot of guinea pigs into their "little" households for their diet
and also to generate heat.
In these sense it is probably that transmission were due to:
1)human-to-human transmission via infected droplets from people with
productive cough during funerals (the most frequently form of transmission
of pneumonic plague),
2)by bites of infected fleas during funerals,
3)by ingestion of infected guinea pigs during funerals.

For control activities it is important to know what is the prevalence of
infected animals (guinea pigs, dogs, pigs) in the neighborhood of these
households.
--
