[3
Date: Fri, 8 May 1998 20:15:55 -0400 (EDT)
From: ottolenghi.1@osu.edu (Abramo Ottolenghi)

The original newspaper article that was carried in its entirety (in Spanish)
in ProMED-PORT Digest v 98 # 43 did speculate that the probable mode of
transmission was via droplets at the funerals. I was not aware of the guinea
pig mortality until I read Dr. Proano's post.
Personally I am at a disadvantage because my information was second hand
from the press but Dr. Proano's post certainly opened some very interesting
possibilities.
The cuy mortality does open the possibility that fleas were involved but as
Dr. Moreira points out pneumonic plague is usually transmitted by droplets.
I would question the probability of the eating of contaminated meat being
the source since the meat is very thoroughly cooked.
In relation to eating cuyes my first recollection is that of an 8 year old
immigrant boy from Italy who observed the horror in his mother's face when
travelling from the coast to Quito by train we were offered cuyes during a
stop.
