[It can be somewhat disconcerting when one is invited to dine in an Andean
village and the house owner reaches under the table, picks up a wriggling
guinea pig, and some 30 minutes later one is eating it. Actually they are
very tastey and nutritious as long as one watches for the bones. While
cooking a bacteraemic guinea pig should kill any _Yersinia_ sp., the
cook(s) would
be at risk through cuts in their hands and/or from rubbing eyes with a
bloody hand. Their intimate relationship with an Andean household would make
them ideal theoretical sentinels as well as flea-feeders ... the reality and
the answers to Dr Moreira's questions still await clarification however. -
